**User Guide for New Features**

Introduction  
In this file, you can find a guide of how to use and test the new features we added to NodeBB.

**Feature Overview**  
We have added three main features:   
1\. Private Posts to Instructors  
2\. Highlight Posts with Instructor Response  
3\. Endorsement of Posts for Instructors. 

How to Use and Visually Test the New Features  
**Feature 1: Private Posts to Instructors**

How to make a Private Post:  
1\. Login as a non-instructor  
![][image1]  
2\. Click on General discussion   
![][image2]  
3\. Click new topic button  
![][image3]  
4\. Toggle the checkmark that says "Make Private"  
![][image4]  
![][image5]  
5\. Fill in details  
![][image6]  
6\. Create the topic

**How to view the Private Post as an Instructor:**  
1\. Login as the admin  
![][image7]  
2\. Click on General Discussion   
![][image8]  
3\. Click of the private post.  
![][image9]  
3\. Click on the private topic and you will see the details of the post. If you are not the admin, you will see a page indicating it is a private post.   
![][image10]  
When I log in as a non admin,   
![][image11]

This will how the post will be shown

![][image12]

**Feature 2: Highlight Posts with Instructor Response/Posts**  
How to create an Instructor Response/Post:  
1\. Login as the Admin  
![][image13]  
2\. Open any topic you wish to post/comment on  
![][image14]  
![][image15]

3\. Fill in your comment and post comment  
![][image16]

How to view highlighted posts:  
1\. Login as any type of member  
![][image17]  
2\. Open topics list  
![][image18]  
3\. All topics with an instructor post/comment will have an icon indicating the instructor commented on that topic.  
![][image19]

**Feature 3: Endorsement of Posts for Instructors**  
How to Endorse a Post as an Instructor:  
1\. Login as the Admin  
![][image20]  
2\. Go to General Discussion  
![][image21]  
3\. Click on any topic.  Click the "Thumbs-Up" icon to endorse the post  
![][image22]  
![][image23]  
Button doesn’t show up for not admin (I logged in from test acc):  
![][image24]  
More display screenshots:

How to view endorsed posts:  
1\. Login as any type of member  
2\. Click on the topic with endorsed post  
3\. If it was endorsed by an instructor, there will be text below the post indicating it was endorsed.  
![][image25]

**Automated Tests**  
**Feature 1: Private Posts to Instructors** [Ellia Yang](mailto:elliay@andrew.cmu.edu)  
Location:  N/A  
Description:  For this feature, we added an extra field, private, to the existing create function, with a default value of false. This was tested by examining the database after topic creation to ensure that they were being created with the field. This was done with the private field both checked and unchecked for the creation of multiple topics. To test if the privileges were sufficient, multiple test accounts were created to simulate different privileges (if the account was the owner of the private post/public post, if the account was an administrator account, etc.)  
Justification: Examining the database is sufficient to reflect whether or not the field exists when a topic is created because our code merely adds a new field to the object. The branch coverage from the original tests are still valid, especially since we set a default value for the field. To test if privileges were sufficient, we simulated all of the possible privilege cases for the code we modified through the manual account testing, which we believe is sufficient for proving that our feature works as intended. 

**Feature 2: Highlight Posts with Instructor Response/Posts** [Yiyao Wang](mailto:yiyaowan@andrew.cmu.edu)  
Location:  test/topics/instructor\_post.js  
Description:  In this file, I added tests to test the new function Topics.hasInstructorPosts. I set up the testing context with a group of normal users, a group of users with the name “instructor”, and two test topics. Then, I wrote test cases to test whether the function accurately reflects whether an instructor has made a post under the topic. The test cases include it should return true if an instructor has replied, return false if no instructor replied, and return false if only regular users replied.   
Justification: The function should reflect whether an instructor has made a post under the topic. I think my test cases are comprehensive enough where they ensure there won’t be any false positives (should not return true if no instructor replied) and false negatives (should not return false if an instructor has replied). Overall, I think the tests for this function tests the main functionality and covers the potential edge cases.

**Feature 3: Endorsement of Posts for Instructors** [Daniel Sung](mailto:dksung@andrew.cmu.edu)  
Location: test/posts/endorse\_post.js  

Description: In this file, I focused on testing the outputs of the Posts.updateEndorsement function. Specifically, I created a temporary post and user in the initial setup. Then, I ran three main test scenarios. First, I created a test in which the function “should update the endorsement status to true” when the function receives the postId and endorse=true as inputs. Second, I created a test in which the function “should update the endorsement status to false” when the function receives the postId and endorse=false as inputs. Lastly, I wrote a test case that confirms that no errors are thrown in between toggling the endorsement status of a post. 

Justification: The main objective of my function was to update the endorsement field in a Post object given an endorsement value. I think that this test suite sufficiently covers the core functionalities of this method. It correctly checks if the endorsement field is updated to the given value and confirms that no errors are thrown whenever the status is switched from true to false and vice versa.
